These hopes are perhaps at the highest point of decades, since Bolivia is awaiting a ruling from the International Court of Justice on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the impetus, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, a positive outlook on the outcome," said Roberto Calzadilla, Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the sentence of the TIJ on giant screens spread across the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will resolve in favor of their country's complaint, so that, after decades of uncertain negotiations, Chile will be forced to negotiate, granting Bolivia a sovereign way out to the sea.
