John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, and this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional test results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service for both students and parents.
The independent schools intend to prepare their students for the further development of their studies and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain a popular theme and sought after in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If we talk to a man in a language he understands, we can get into his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can enter his heart."
This quote reminds us that we cannot only depend on English when we want to create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of this year's recent examinations, we found that languages are at the top of the table, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum A rating.
These data, collected in the 74 schools under the SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained the maximum A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are favouring foreign languages as vital skills which will undoubtedly serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
A UK Commission survey on Employment and Skills in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons for employers’ difficulty in filling vacancies, 17% concerned the lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowing other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential employment opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with an aptitude for life like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of competition.
According to a survey by YouGov to more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a ratio of two digits, 15%.
So investing now in language teaching is important for today's children.
The domain of several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children with better chances of finding a relevant job.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK for the 2020 horizon, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a set of languages of choice in independent schools, supported by specialized teaching staff in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the skills necessary for success, whatever the future holds for them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages remain of fundamental importance for the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it on education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "enabled in international communication".
Independent schools will continue to provide this option with diversity and excellence for young Scots.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
