North Korea says "no thinking" to unilateral disarmament without confidence
The foreign minister of North Korea told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions was aggravating mistrust of the United States and that there was no way for the country to unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" last year, such as the interruption of nuclear and missile testing, the dismantling of the nuclear testing centre and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we see no corresponding US response," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can proceed with our disarmament first."
Although Ri has recycled already known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it takes gradual steps, its statements appear to be significant in that they do not in any way reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang's previous positions.
Ri mentioned a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever held between an acting US President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim undertook to work towards the "denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula", while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950–53 Korean war, but the United States claims that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted appeals to soften the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "denuclearization first" and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, opposing until the "declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is exacerbating our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the US leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: "If the party interested in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this deadlock".
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was drastically different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that directing North Korean rockets towards U.S. territory was inevitable after "Mr. President Bad" Trump called Kim "the rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who had threatened to destroy North Korea "completely last year, filled Kim with praise for his courage in taking steps towards disarmament, but said that there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea's denuclearisation.
On Wednesday, Trump stated that he did not have a calendar for this, stating that "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until denuclearisation is complete, final and verifiable."
The Security Council unanimously reinforced the sanctions against North Korea imposed since 2006, in an attempt to strangle the financing of North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and declared after visiting Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, although later North Korea denounced him for "making gangster demands.
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea undertook to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States "takes appropriate measures".
Pompeo stated that Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" they sought were the security guarantees taken by Trump in Singapore, as well as initiatives to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course that teaches them to rest long enough.
A new course at Harvard University this year has put all its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the macho culture of studying in caffeine-impregnated "directs".
One teacher concluded that the students of this university at the top of the world ranking often had no idea about the most basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, who believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for the course came after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?"
The young woman stated that no one had ever mentioned the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to the improvement of general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, stated that the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, shoes and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to collect to the bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it won't change students' behavior instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, as we all have the right to know the health effects of smoking option," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "direct doing" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we sleep enough and with quality should be a "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid getting fat, because sleep deprivation puts the brain into hunger mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a course for the entire campus, he said.
The next step, according to your expectations, is to ask all graduate students who attend a similar study program before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider using an alarm for bedtime, as well as waking up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the electronic screens and LED lighting, which may disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to trouble sleeping.
