China has announced a 14% jump in the number of its citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820 000 people are affected in the country, the health authorities said.
Around 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases result from transmissions through sexual intercourse, which marks a change from the past.
HIV has traditionally spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who contracted HIV in this way was reduced to almost zero, the Chinese health authorities said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, in terms of annual annual variation, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
The transmission of HIV through sexual intercourse is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but it is said that discrimination against the LGBT community is frequent.
Studies have estimated that, due to the conservative values of the country, 70 to 90% of men who have had sexual relations with other men end up marrying women.
Many of the disease transmissions derive from inadequate sexual protection in these relationships.
The Chinese government has promised since 2003 universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to solve the problem.
