National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
Further investigations are being carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands with the aim of revealing how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, carried out by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and fruit bats, as well as long-eared browns and Daubenton bats at the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations scattered around the property to follow the activities of bats along the station.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS personnel and volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will evaluate the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviour on a territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, an advisor for the conservation of the nature of the NTS, expects the results to reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works that affect the dormitories and make the habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning also pose a threat, together with flypapers and some chemical treatments of construction materials, in addition to attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo localization technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly conduct studies, inspections of dormitories and sometimes rescues.
He also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The owner of the property, David Thompson, says it's the perfect territory for them.
"Here in Threave we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there is still much about the bats we do not know, so the work we do here and in the other properties will help us to know more about what they need to flourish".
He highlighted the importance of checking for bats before maintaining the properties, as the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dormitory can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it's illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish chief of Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
It was said by her: "We still have much to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we simply do not know how their populations are taking revenge".
